The fluorescence lifetimes exhibited by the CDs are multi-exponential in nature due to the presence of different chemical environment [33]. The time resolved fluorescence spectra were recorded at 440, 450 and 470 nm as shown in the Fig. 4
                        g. The CDs exhibit triple exponential decay where the decay trace can be fitted with triple exponential decay expression (I(t) = A1e(-t/τ
                        1
                        ) + A2
                        e(-t/τ
                        2
                        ) + A3
                        e(-t/τ
                        3
                        ), where I(t) represents intensity of decay at recorded time t, A1, A2 and A3 correspond to pre-exponential factors and τ1, τ2 and τ3 represent individual lifetime values) [34,35]. The average lifetime values of CDs corresponding to 490 nm (0.29 ns & 0.28 ns) and 535 nm (0.51 ns & 0.14 ns) recorded at different excitations (440 & 450 nm) exhibit multi-exponential decay nature. The ST 4 tabulates the individual and average lifetime values of CDs at 440, 450 and 470 nm excitations.
